istory of acute abdominal pain, vomiting and diarrhoea. He looks unwell and is dehydrated. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. A CT scan is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely radiological diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abdominal aortic aneurysm","Lymphoma","Retroperitoneal sarcoma","Tuberculous adenitis","Renal cell carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture suggests gastroenteritis. What is seen on the CT scan is almost certainly an incidental finding and unrelated to this patient\u0027s current illness. There is a collection of enlarged para-aortic lymph nodes. It is estimated that more than 30% of abdominal CT scans performed in the Emergency Department will have at least one incidental finding. Any of the listed options could present in such a way. In this case, the most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Etuberculous adenitis\u003C/strong\u003E - given the patient\u0027s origins and the radiological finding of a rim of calcification of the enlarged para-aortic lymph nodes. The arrow points to the enlarged nodes, situated between the aorta and inferior vena cava.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Incidental findings are very common in abdominal CTs."],"references":["Thompson R, Wojcik SM, Grant WD, et al. Incidental Findings on CT Scans in the Emergency Department. Emerging Med Int 2011; 10.1155/2011/624847"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94337"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1880"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17798"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17799"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17798"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8bad76cb-b3c2-40be-b65f-43c8a425433f.jpg","thumbUrl":"htt